1. Project overview:
Mini Remote Controlled Firefighting Robot is a personal embedded systems project designed to demonstrate a remotely operated firefighting platform. The robot is controlled through a web-based interface, allowing users to navigate the vehicle and operate its firefighting mechanisms from a safe distance. 


2. Features:
-Four-directional movement (forward, backward, left, and right)
-Integrated water pumping system using an onboard water tank
-Integrated sand-blowing system using an onboard sand reservoir
-Independently adjustable pump and blower directions for more effective firefighting
-Real-time system status updates
Browser-based web interface for remote control


3. Hardware:
Relay module: 2-channel Songle SRD-05VDC-SL-C 
Motor driver: L298N Dual H-Bridge
Buck converters: LM2596 adjustable
Servo: TowerPro MG996R
Controller: ESP32 DevKit V1
Battery pack: 3S 11.1V 18650 Li-ion Battery Pack
Blower: 75×75×30 mm 12V Brushless Centrifugal Blower (7530)
Pump: 370 DC Mini Diaphragm Water Pump (12V)
Chassis: 6 wheels aluminium DIY tank chassis


4. Software
The robot firmware is developed using Visual Studio Code with PlatformIO, targeting the ESP-IDF framework. The embedded application is written in C, while the user interface is implemented using HTML and served directly by the ESP32's built-in HTTP server.

The robot operates in Wi-Fi Access Point (AP) mode, allowing users to connect directly to the ESP32 without requiring an external router. Once connected, users can access the web interface through a browser to remotely control the robot and monitor its status in real time.



5. How to use
Connect the 3S Li-ion battery.
Turn on the main power switch.
The ESP32 starts in Access Point mode.
Connect your phone or laptop to the robot's Wi-Fi network.
Default SSID: ESP32-Access-Point
Password: 12345678
Open a browser.
Navigate to: http://192.168.4.1/


*Note: This robot is intended as a prototype and educational project. It is suitable for demonstrating remote firefighting concepts but is not designed for use in real emergency situations.

